Introduction ¶

Many people struggle to get loans due to insufficient or non-existent credit histories. And this population is often taken advantage of by untrustworthy lenders. Home Credit strives to broaden financial inclusion for this underserved population by providing a positive and safe borrowing experience. Our goal in this project is to help the Home Credit Loan Servicing team achieve their goal by building a model tuned for maximum accuracy that will predict the clients capability of loan repayment. The model output will be a probability of loan repayment failure.

Target variable:
1 - client with payment difficulties: he/she had late payment more than X days on at least one of the first Y installments of the loan in our sample.
0 - all other cases.

# Function to calculate missing values by column# Funct 
def missing_values_table(df):
        # Total missing values
        mis_val = df.isnull().sum()
        # Percentage of missing values
        mis_val_percent = 100 * df.isnull().sum() / len(df)
        # Make a table with the results
        mis_val_table = pd.concat([mis_val, mis_val_percent], axis=1,ignore_index= True)
        # Rename the columns
        mis_val_table = mis_val_table.rename(
        columns = {0 : 'Missing Values', 1 : '% of Total Values'})
        # Sort the table by percentage of missing descending
        mis_val_table = mis_val_table[
            mis_val_table.iloc[:,1] != 0].sort_values(
        '% of Total Values', ascending=False).round(1)
        # Print some summary information
        print ("The dataframe has " + str(df.shape[1]) + " columns.\n"      
            "There are " + str(mis_val_table.shape[0]) +
              " columns that have missing values.")
        # Return the dataframe with missing information
        return mis_val_table

# extract continuous columns
all_numerical_cols = list(app_train.select_dtypes(exclude='object').columns)

# continuous  columns are all columns excluding target and flags columns
cont_cols = [col for col in all_numerical_cols if col != "TARGET" and col[:5]!='FLAG_']

# draw histograms for each continuous column    
plt.figure(figsize=(25, 50))
for i, col in enumerate(cont_cols):
    plt.subplot(16, 5, i+1)
    sns.distplot(app_train[col])

Data Modeling ¶

The interquartile range (IQR) is a measurement of the spread of values in the middle 50%. If an observation is 1.5 times the interquartile range more than the third quartile (Q3) or 1.5 times the interquartile range less than the first quartile (Q1), it is considered and outlier.

Impute Outliers ¶

Due to skewness in the data we will replace the outliers determined by IQR approach with the median values.

In [34]:
#Remove Outliers using IQR
def remove_outliers(df, columns):
    for col in columns:
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
        df = df[(df[col] >= lower_bound) & (df[col] <= upper_bound)]
    return df
In [35]:
def remove_outliers_iqr_values(df, columns):
    """
    Remove outlier values from a specified column in a pandas dataframe
    using the interquartile range (IQR) method without removing rows.
    
    Parameters:
    df (pandas.DataFrame): The input dataframe
    col (str): The name of the column to remove outlier values from
    
    Returns:
    pandas.DataFrame: The modified dataframe with outlier values replaced by NaN
    """
    for col in columns:
        Q1 = df[col].quantile(0.25)
        Q3 = df[col].quantile(0.75)
        IQR = Q3 - Q1
        lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5*IQR
        upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5*IQR
        df.loc[(df[col] < lower_bound) | (df[col] > upper_bound), col] = np.nan
    return df

def impute_nulls_median(df):
    """
    Impute null values in a pandas dataframe with the median of each column.
    
    Parameters:
    df (pandas.DataFrame): The input dataframe
    
    Returns:
    pandas.DataFrame: The modified dataframe with null values imputed with median
    """
    median = df.median()
    df = df.fillna(median)
    return df

Results ¶

Accuracy: Logistic Regression Model: 0.92 Random Forest Classifier Model: 0.92 Gradient Boosting Classifier Model: 0.92

Even though Logistic Regression Model accuracy is the highest, the Precision, Recall and F1 score, all are zero. A zero value for any of these metrics is generally not a desirable outcome, as it indicates that the classifier is not performing well in identifying positive instances. Will investigate why the classifier is not making any positive predictions and make necessary changes to improve its performance. Tried creating a balanced dataframe that will have the same amount of data for each target variable from the app_train dataset, but the model did not lead to a better performaces. The accuracy rate were in the range of 50's. Also, the hyperparameter grid search was done all the three models to get the best hyperparameters. The best results of the grid search were used as hyperparameters when creating the final models.

Random Forest provided the model i chose due to the comparable accuarcy sore of 92.12% and ROC AUC score of 91% and with the least runtime than GBC. The Cross validation scores on the model are all consistent and hence show that the model is not overfitted.
